T2  - PLANT ECOLOGY & DIVERSITY
AB  - Background: Plant and soil nitrogen stable isotope (N-15) can integrate several fundamental biogeochemical processes in ecosystem nitrogen dynamics, and reflect characteristics of ecosystem nitrogen cycling.Aims: We investigated how climate change influenced plant-soil nitrogen cycling by relating soil N-15, plant N-15 and N-15 (difference between soil and plant N-15) with climatic factors.Methods: Field investigation was conducted in temperate grasslands in Inner Mongolia during August 2015. Plant N-15, soil N-15 and N-15 were determined, and their relationships with climatic factors were examined by simple regression analyses and general linear models.Results: Soil N-15 was significantly higher than plant N-15, and there was a positive linear correlation between them. Soil and plant N-15 were negatively related with mean annual precipitation (MAP) and positively with mean annual temperature (MAT); conversely, N-15 was positively related with MAP and negatively with MAT.Conclusion: Soil N-15 was dominantly controlled by MAT, while it was MAP for plant N-15. Climate factors influenced plant N-15 not only through their effects on soil nitrogen dynamics but also strategies of plant nitrogen acquisition. Thus, compared with plant N-15, soil N-15 can more accurately reflect soil nitrogen dynamics, while plant N-15 may integrate soil nitrogen dynamics and plant nitrogen acquisition.
