T2  - GEOMICROBIOLOGY JOURNAL
AB  - Soil microbes are central to carbon cycling, acting as both sources and sinks of carbon, thereby influencing global climate dynamics. Climatic changes-elevated CO2, altered precipitation patterns, and rising temperatures-profoundly affect microbial community structure and function, modulating carbon release, fixation, and stabilization processes. This review examines key microbial mechanisms driving soil carbon dynamics under climate stress, including enzyme activity, microbial functional traits, and the microbial carbon pump (MCP). Climate change exerts dual effects on microbial activity, promoting CO2 emissions (positive feedback) while also enabling carbon stabilization (negative feedback). Although single-factor studies have elucidated individual responses, the interactive effects of multiple climatic drivers remain insufficiently explored. Advances in metagenomics, molecular tools, and simulation models have enhanced our understanding of microbial responses, yet challenges in data integration and predictive modeling persist. Incorporating microbial management strategies-such as organic amendments, reduced tillage, and crop diversification-into climate-resilient agricultural practices can enhance soil carbon sequestration and ecosystem sustainability. This review emphasizes the urgent need for interdisciplinary research to decipher complex microbe-climate interactions and integrate microbial strategies into climate policy frameworks for effective mitigation and long-term soil health.
