AB  - Increasing concentrations of the climate-sensitive trace-gas carbon dioxide (CO2) in the atmosphere necessitates the development of new concepts with the aim of conserving fossil energy. The biomass of the terrestrial vegetation constitutes a substantial reservoir for CO2 which in principal is suited to store CO2 from anthropogenic emissions. At the same time biomass can substitute fossil energy sources. The present paper describes the significance of the terrestrial vegetation for the global carbon cycle and investigates to what extend agriculture and forestry can contribute to mitigate the threat of increasing and atmospheric CO2-concentrations. Existing investigations reveal that in highly industrialized countries only a small percentage of the CO2 emitted from fossil sources can be sequestered by forests and/or can be substituted by agriculturally produced biomass (''energy plants'') and waste wood used as energy source, mainly since only limited acre age can be provided for afforestation and the agricultural production of biomass. Agriculture and forestry differ substantially in their methods to produce biomass and therefore they contribute in different ways to reduce the emission of CO2 from fossil sources. Whereas agriculture mainly can provide ''shortlived'' biomass as substitute for fossil energy sources (energy plants), in forestry, emphasis is layed on management practices which lead to a longer lasting sequestration of atmospheric CO2 in trees and ''longlived'' wooden products. In addition, forestry can provide waste wood as substitute for fossil energy sources. Despite the fact that, in industrialized countries, only a modest fraction of the totally consumed energy can be replaced by energy stemming from biomass, agriculture and forestry, nevertheless, in combination with other sustainalble methods of energy production, should make a contribution to conserve fossil energy resources, even though in highly Industrialized countries the reduction of energy consumption is presently the most effective means to abate the CO2-problem.
