AB  - Soil microorganisms are central to the global carbon cycle, functioning simultaneously as agents of carbon release and as facilitators of carbon sequestration, thus influencing climate change trajectories. Alterations in atmospheric CO2 concentrations, precipitation regimes, and temperature patterns critically shape microbial community structures and their functional roles in carbon transformation processes. This review delves into the multifaceted pathways through which microbes regulate soil carbon fluxes amidst a changing climate, emphasizing enzymatic degradation, functional trait adaptations, and the microbial carbon pump (MCP) framework. The intricate balance between microbial-driven carbon emissions, which can amplify climate warming, and mechanisms of carbon stabilization that offer mitigating feedbacks, is thoroughly examined. Despite significant progress from controlled single-variable experiments, the synergistic impacts of multiple interacting climatic stressors on microbial processes remain inadequately explored, highlighting a pressing gap in current research. Emerging methodologies in high-throughput sequencing, metagenomic profiling, and predictive modeling have begun to illuminate microbial responses at finer resolutions, yet the complexity of translating these findings into actionable insights remains challenging. The integration of microbiome-focused soil management strategies - such as bioorganic amendments, reduced tillage practices, and crop system diversification - into broader climate resilience frameworks presents a viable pathway for enhancing soil carbon stocks and promoting agroecosystem sustainability. This synthesis advocates for a transdisciplinary research paradigm that bridges microbial ecology with climate science and policy, fostering innovative microbial interventions to mitigate greenhouse gas emissions and reinforce ecosystem adaptive capacities.
